Brian Ceccarelli presents us with the fallacy of False Dichotomy in stating that we must accept every thing in the books attributed to Peter or we must discount every other book of antiquity:   Mr Ceccarelli you seem to be stating that we must accept accept everything written in every historical document.  Somehow I doubt do that yourself that.  Thus since I doubt you accept everything written in every historical document I would ask how you can thereby objectively justify complete faith in the words of the books attributed to Peter.   I shall now give an example of a document from antiquity which I am sure you reject; it dates from the time of Ramses II (This was first presented here by Matthew Wiener).  These inscriptions were carved soon after a battle and were carved with the Pharoah\s specific approval so we have true originals rather than mere copies.  This account records the the battle of Kadesh (circa 1285 BC) which occurred on the river Orontes (about 100 miles south of Aleppo).  The Egyptians won this battle with the Hittites and Ramses had his victory inscribed all over the place.  A few of of these inscriptions have survived in near perfect form.  It is a record of how the Pharoah pretty much single-handedly defeated the Hittites after being separated from his troops.   Note that the Egyptian wavers back and forth between first and third person.  The following is from Miriam Lichtheim`s _Ancient Egyptian Literature_ volume II.  \tMy majesty caused the forces of the foes from Hitti to fall \ton their faces one upon the other as crocodiles fall into \tthe water of the Orontes.  I was after them like a griffin; \tI attacked all the countries I alone.  For my infantry and \tmy chariotry had deserted me; not one of them stood looking \tback.  As I live as Ra loves me as my father Atum favors \tme everything that my majesty has told I did it in truth \tin the presence of my infantry and my chariotry.  (Note: This paragraph records not only Ramses divine word but also that there were thousands of witnesses to the event.  Now from the heart of  battle.)  \tThen his majesty drove at a gallop and charged the forces \tof the Foe from Hitti being alone by himself none other \twith him.  His majesty proceeded to look about him and \tfound 2500 chariots ringing him on his way out ...  \tNo officer was with me no charioteer \tNo soldier of the army no shield-bearer; \tMy infantry my chariotry yielded before them \tNot one of them stood firm to fight with them. \tHis majesty spoke: What is this father Amun? \tIs it right for a father to ignore his son? \tAre my deeds a matter for you to ignore? \tDo I not walk and stand at your word? \tI have not neglected an order you gave. \tToo great is he the great lord of Egypt \tTo allow aliens to step on his path! \tWhat are these Asiatics to you O Amun \tThe wretches ignorant of god? \tHave I not made for you many great monuments \t... \tI call to you my father Amun \tI am among a host of strangers; \tAll countries are arrayed against me \tI am alone there\s none with me! \t... \tThe labors of many people are nothing \tAmun is more helpful than they; \tI came here by the command of your mouth \tO Amun I have not transgressed your command!  \tNow though I prayed in a distant land \tMy voice resounded in Southern Thebes. \tI found Amun came when I called to him \tHe gave me his hand and I rejoiced. \tHe called from behind as if near by: \tForward I am with you \tI your father my hand is with you \tI prevail over a hundred thousand men \tI am lord of victory lover of valor! \tI found my heart stout my breast in joy \tAll I did succeeded I was like Mont. \t... \tI slaughtered among them at my will \tNot one looked behind him \tNot one turned around \tWhoever fell down did not rise. \t... \tOne called out to the other saying: \tNo man is he who is among us \tIt is Seth great-of-strength Baal in person; \tNot deeds of man are these his doings \tThey are of one who is unique \tWho fights a hundred thousand without soldiers and chariots \tCome quick flee before him \tTo seek life and breathe air; \tFor he who attempts to get close to him \tHis hands all his limbs grow limp. \tOne cannot hold either bow or spears \tWhen one sees him come racing along! \tMy majesty hunted them like a griffin \tI slaughtered among them unceasingly.  So you see Brian we have a few original manuscripts recording the miraculous  battle between the Ramses and the Hittites.  Do you reject them as being *completely* true? I suspect you do and if so then do you also in your own words:       question the existence of Alexander the Great Tilgrath Pilisar III      Nero Caligula Josephus Cyrus the Great Artexerxes?  Do you also thereby question all their documents? That`s the problem with your all or nothing approach.  Many ancient people used to mix a bit of fancy with their facts.  So for you to say that we must either accept all of Peter (and the rest of the New Testament) or accept no records of antiquity at all forces you thereby to accept the verity of documents you probably do not find completely credible.   As to your other argument that so many people have testified to Jesus that he must be true:    I have three points.    First this is argumentum ad populum (ie: appeal to popular opinion); you cannot vote on truth.  For instance do the millions of Hindu\s past and present who testify to the reality of Brahma constitute actual evidence for the existence of Brahma? How would you answer your own question in regards to the testimony of Hindus:  \tWith a scoff of your keyboard with near complete ignorance of  \t the testimonies are you going to say that that is all complete  \t hooey?  If you do so scoff then how do you objectively justify your own special pleading?  Second it is not at all clear that King Solomon or King David testified to Jesus.  You can claim it to be clear but that does not make it true.   Third it is quite arguable that Abraham Lincoln was not Christian and that he had both a public and a private view of Christianity.  In fact there was much discussion about it in his day (yes he was publically accused of being a deist.  Oh my).  I am presently collecting a FAQ for Lincoln as I\ve previously done for Tyre Jefferson and etc.    \t\t\t\tLater

